<TITLE> EU plans emergency teams for mass refugees arrivals </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BRUSSELS, Wed Feb 18,(bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A team of on-call asylum experts should be created to help EU states like Greece and Malta cope when faced with mass arrivals of asylum seekers, the bloc's executive said on Wednesday. Countries at the bloc's coastal borders are struggling to deal with increasing numbers of refugees and migrants arriving by sea. The UN refugees agency has criticised poor conditions in crammed refugee centres in states such as Greece and Italy. The European Commission proposed on Wednesday to set up a pool asylum experts from across the 27-nation bloc who could be sent to countries in need of help within five days. The experts would help with emergency accommodation, transport, and medical assistance and be organised by an EU asylum support office which the EU also proposed to set up on Wednesday. "The asylum office could be operational before the end of 2010, it is eagerly awaited by Mediterranean countries like Malta, Cyprus and Greece who are a bit overwhelmed by asylum seekers," the EU's top migration official Jacques Barrot told Reuters in an interview last month. The asylum office needs to be agreed by EU governments and lawmakers
